Here's how to handle each scenario with MSTest 3.10+ attributes and patterns:

## 1. Windows-only (registry tests)

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[OSCondition(OperatingSystems.Windows)]
public void Registry_ReadsExpectedValue()
{
    var value = Registry.GetValue(@"HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE\SOFTWARE\MyApp", "Setting", null);
    Assert.IsNotNull(value);
}
```

## 2. Skip in CI (requires local GPU)

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[CICondition(ConditionMode.Exclude)]
public void RenderScene_ProducesExpectedOutput()
{
    var result = GpuRenderer.Render(scene);
    Assert.IsNotNull(result);
}
```

## 3. Flaky external API (retry)

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[Retry(3)]
[Timeout(10000)]
public async Task WeatherApi_ReturnsForecast()
{
    var forecast = await _weatherClient.GetForecastAsync(_testContext.CancellationToken);
    Assert.IsNotNull(forecast);
}
```

Use `[Retry(3)]` (MSTest 3.9+) only for genuinely flaky external dependencies — not to mask race conditions.

## 4. Cleanup temp files even on failure

Use `[TestCleanup]` — it runs regardless of test outcome:

```csharp
[TestClass]
public sealed class FileProcessingTests
{
    private string _tempFile = string.Empty;

    [TestInitialize]
    public void Setup()
    {
        _tempFile = Path.GetTempFileName();
    }

    [TestMethod]
    public void ProcessFile_WritesExpectedContent()
    {
        FileProcessor.Process(_tempFile);
        Assert.AreEqual("expected", File.ReadAllText(_tempFile));
    }

    [TestCleanup]
    public void Cleanup()
    {
        if (File.Exists(_tempFile))
            File.Delete(_tempFile);
    }
}
```

Alternatively, implement `IDisposable` on the test class — MSTest calls `Dispose` after each test (after `[TestCleanup]`).

---

**Execution guarantee order:** TestMethod → `[TestCleanup]` → `DisposeAsync` → `Dispose` — cleanup always runs even if the test throws.
